04856nam a22005655i 9780226432984DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020022828  a9780226432984  a(DE-B1597)572510  a(OCoLC)1253313595  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQE721.2.E97bS78 2021 4aQE721.2.E97bS78 2021 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a560/.17922231 aStuart, Anthony J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVanished Giants :bThe Lost World of the Ice Age /cAnthony J. Stuart. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b69 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Crises in the History of Life -- t3. The Ice Age and the Megafauna -- t4. Cold Case: The Search for the Ice Age Killer -- t5. Northern Eurasia: Woolly Rhinos, Cave Bears, and Giant Deer -- t6. North America: Mastodon, Ground Sloths, and Sabertooth Cats -- t7. South America: Ground Sloths and Glyptodonts -- t8. Sahul: Giant Marsupials, a Thunderbird, and a Huge Lizard -- t9. Madagascar: Giant Lemurs, Elephant Birds, and Dwarf Hippos -- t10. New Zealand: Land of the Moa -- t11. Island Megafauna -- t12. Megafaunal Survival: Sub-Saharan Africa and Southern Asia -- t13. Summary and Conclusions: The Global Pattern of Megafaunal Extinctions -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix: Dating the Past -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLong after the extinction of dinosaurs, when humans were still in the stone age, woolly rhinos, mammoths, mastodons, sabertooth cats, giant ground sloths, and many other spectacular large animals that are no longer with us roamed the Earth. These animals are regarded as “Pleistocene megafauna,” named for the geological era in which they lived—also known as the Ice Age. In Vanished Giants: The Lost World of the Ice Age, paleontologist Anthony J. Stuart explores the lives and environments of these animals, moving between six continents and several key islands. Stuart examines the animals themselves via what we’ve learned from fossil remains, and he describes the landscapes, climates, vegetation, ecological interactions, and other aspects of the animals’ existence. Illustrated throughout, Vanished Giants also offers a picture of the world as it was tens of thousands of years ago when these giants still existed. Unlike the case of the dinosaurs, there was no asteroid strike to blame for the end of their world. Instead, it appears that the giants of the Ice Age were driven to extinction by climate change, human activities—especially hunting—or both. Drawing on the latest evidence provided by radiocarbon dating, Stuart discusses these possibilities. The extinction of Ice Age megafauna can be seen as the beginning of the so-called Sixth Extinction, which is happening right now. This has important implications for understanding the likely fate of present-day animals in the face of contemporary climate change and vastly increasing human populations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnimals, Fossil. 0aExtinct animals. 0aExtinction (Biology) 0aExtinction (Biology). 0aGlacial epoch. 0aPaleontologyyPleistocene. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aice age, lost, forgotten, extinction, time period, era, history, historical, ancient, megafauna, science, scientific, academic, scholarly, research, dinosaurs, woolly, rhinos, mammoths, mastodons, sabertooth, sloths, large, animals, pleistocene, geological, geology, paleontologist, paleontology, landscape, climate, vegetation, habitat, change, global warming, contemporary.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertU